  <article class="prose">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>
    <p>
      This page documents how Silicon Logic turns local inference runs into claims that can be inspected later.
      The first public methodology version is intentionally conservative: it prefers repeatable measurements,
      explicit configuration, and signed artifacts over broad but fragile coverage.
    </p>

    <h2>Hardware Configuration</h2>
    <p>
      Test systems are described by chip family, memory capacity, operating-system build, runtime versions, and
      power state. Apple Silicon systems are treated as unified-memory machines rather than as a CPU plus a
      discrete accelerator, because memory pressure and bandwidth shape local inference behavior across the
      whole machine. Results that depend on thermal state or sustained load are marked as such.
    </p>
    <p>
      The methodology avoids pretending that one laptop represents a whole product line. When a result is
      specific to a memory tier, storage configuration, cooling envelope, or runtime setting, the artifact is
      expected to say so.
    </p>

    <h2>Quantization Choices</h2>
    <p>
      Production-class local inference is normally evaluated with 4-bit quantization because that is where many
      consumer systems cross from "can load the model" to "can run the model with useful context." Silicon Logic
      reports formats such as <code>Q4_K_M</code>, <code>Q4_K_S</code>, and <code>Q8_0</code> as runtime inputs,
      not as abstract quality claims. A smaller file can reduce memory bandwidth pressure while also changing
      accuracy, cache behavior, and runtime kernel selection.
    </p>
    <p>
      When an article compares formats, it should identify the model source, conversion path, quantization
      metadata, and runtime version. The point is not to crown a universal format. The point is to make the
      tradeoff visible enough that readers can map it onto their own constraints.
    </p>

    <h2>Measurement Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      Throughput is reported as tokens per second after the prompt has been ingested unless the article states
      otherwise. Time to first token measures the reader-visible delay from request submission to the first
      generated token. First-decode-token latency isolates the transition from prefill into decode, which can
      expose runtime behavior that a single aggregate throughput number hides.
    </p>
    <p>
      Runs are repeated, summarized with medians and tail values, and kept with enough raw samples to make
      outliers visible. Silicon Logic prefers a smaller set of measurements with clear provenance over a wide
      table whose assumptions cannot be reconstructed.
    </p>

    <h2>Signed Runs</h2>
    <p>
      Benchmark articles may attach a BenchmarkRun artifact. The artifact records runtime versions, hardware
      configuration, model identifiers, prompt shape, measured samples, and summary statistics. Signed artifacts
      are referenced from the article and can be verified against the repository history.
    </p>
    <p>
      The visible signed-run badge is not decoration. It means the numeric claims in that section point back to
      a concrete artifact rather than to a private spreadsheet or a screenshot that will disappear.
    </p>

    <h2>Methodology Version</h2>
    <p>
      The launch methodology starts at <strong>v1.0</strong>. Version bumps are reserved for changes that alter
      what a reader should infer from a number: new run fields, changed aggregation rules, different warm-up
      handling, or revised latency definitions.
    </p>

    <h2>Changelog</h2>
    <dl>
      <dt>v1.0</dt>
      <dd>Initial public methodology for local inference reviews, benchmark reports, and signed BenchmarkRun artifacts.</dd>
    </dl>
  </article>
